WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.480
What Is Digital Transformation?

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:07.120
Digital transformation is a tough thing to explain.

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:11.280
The way I try to explain digital transformation to anyone is,

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:16.639
imagine a river and you get to stand beside that river as an advisor to a company.

00:00:16.639 --> 00:00:21.600
And constantly floating down that river are little crates and in each one of those crates

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:28.320
is a new technology or a fad or a new product. And it's your job as a company to quickly

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:32.560
evaluate each crate going down the river and identify, does that have something in it that

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:37.759
can help me? Does that have something in it that could hurt me? And how hard is it going to be for

00:00:37.759 --> 00:00:42.400
me to jump in the river and fish out the crate and drag it back and try to make use out of it?

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:46.480
And that's the really hard part. And a company that tries to reach every single one in the

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:50.080
river and pull it out is going to quickly find themselves exhausted and overwhelmed

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:53.439
and have a hard time trying to cobble together what they just pulled out of the river.

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:58.959
A company that's falling behind says that's energy and effort that's not necessarily always

00:00:58.959 --> 00:01:02.480
worth it. So I'm going to just stick with what I've got. I'm going to let those sail on,

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:05.360
pass me to the next person standing behind me on the side of the river.

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:10.959
But a company that's really good at digital transformation, at applying technology for

00:01:10.959 --> 00:01:16.320
competitive advantage, is good at seeing that crate float by, quickly deciding, is that crate

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:20.480
worth it? And then once I've got it on the shore, can I quickly put it to work so I can get back to

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:25.279
looking at the river and seeing what's coming down? As a company, if you have a center of

00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:30.639
excellence of data scientists who are developing things, really valuable things, but they're hard

00:01:30.639 --> 00:01:35.040
for you to leverage in other departments, other groups, or even commercially publicly,

00:01:35.839 --> 00:01:40.800
PositConnect in this context was one of those that you quickly see coming down and say,

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:44.800
like, okay, this is going to work. To me, it's a little underdog technology that helps us

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:53.279
bridge a really big gap.

